.TH AUDITFS 4
.SH NAME
auditfs \- tamper-evident audit-log file server
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B auditfs
.RB [ \-f
.IR backing-file ]
.RB [ \-k
.IR signer-keyfile ]
.PP
.B auditverify
.RB [ \-k
.IR pubkeyfile ]
.RI [ chainfile ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.I Auditfs
is a Styx file server, normally mounted at
.BR /mnt/audit ,
that records security-relevant events as an append-only,
tamper-evident log. It serves these files:
.TP
.B log
Write-only. A write of the form
.RI `` source\  event\  message ''
is sealed into one record: the server assigns the sequence
number and timestamp (so a writer cannot forge ordering or
backdate an entry) and extends a SHA-256 hash chain over the
record. Reads return empty.
.TP
.B chain
Read-only. The sealed records, oldest first, one per line:
.IR seq \  timestamp \  source \  event \  hash \  message .
.TP
.B head
Read-only. The current chain tip and last sequence number,
.RI `` hash\  seq '',
suitable for publishing or shipping off-host as an anchor.
.TP
.B verify
Read-only. Recomputes the chain and returns
.RB `` ok\  \fIn\fP ''
or
.RB `` broken\ at\ seq\  \fIn\fP ''.
.TP
.B pubkey
Read-only. The audit public key (when a signer key is configured
with
.BR \-k ),
for distribution to verifiers.
.TP
.B ctl
Write-only. Writing
.B checkpoint
appends a checkpoint record naming the current head. When a signer
key is configured the checkpoint is signed (the certificate is
verifiable with the
.B pubkey
above, giving non-repudiation without sharing any secret).
.PP
Integrity is a linear hash chain:
.IR H [0]
= SHA-256(genesis), and
.IR H [ n ]
= SHA-256(\fIH\fP[\fIn\fP\-1] \(em record). Editing, reordering,
or deleting any record changes that hash and every later one,
so a recomputation that disagrees with the stored chain proves
tampering. The chain is tamper-\fIevident\fP: an externally
anchored
.B head
detects even a full rewrite of the backing file. At startup the
chain is recomputed from the backing file and a break is reported
on standard error.
.PP
Access control is by namespace placement. Bind only the
.B log
file (write-only) into a subject's name space and it can append
to its own audit trail but cannot read or rewrite history; an
agent thus cannot cover its tracks.
.PP
The backing file defaults to
.BR /usr/inferno/audit/log ;
its containing directory must already exist. With
.B \-f
a different path may be given. With
.B \-k
a signer keyfile (as produced by
.IR createsignerkey (8))
is loaded; checkpoints are then signed.
.PP
.I Auditverify
is the standalone offline verifier. It recomputes the hash chain
over a
.I chainfile
(default standard input) and reports
.RB `` ok ''
or the first break; with
.B \-k
it also checks every checkpoint signature against the audit public
key.
.SH EXAMPLE
.EX
auth/createsignerkey -a ed25519 -f /keydb/auditkey audit
mount {auditfs -k /keydb/auditkey} /mnt/audit
echo 'login unlock user=alice aal=3' >/mnt/audit/log
echo checkpoint >/mnt/audit/ctl
cat /mnt/audit/pubkey >/tmp/auditpub
cat /mnt/audit/chain | auditverify -k /tmp/auditpub
.EE
.SH SOURCE
.B /appl/cmd/auditfs.b
.br
.B /appl/cmd/auditverify.b
.br
.B /appl/lib/auditchain.b
.SH SEE ALSO
.IR keyring (2),
.IR createsignerkey (8)
.br
.B doc/compliance/audit-log-design.md
.SH BUGS
Records since the last signed
.B ctl
checkpoint are protected by the hash chain but are not yet covered
by a signature; checkpoint frequently (and on high-value events) to
bound that window. The signer key is held by
.I auditfs
itself; moving it into
.IR factotum (4),
so the server never holds the private key, is a hardening step. A
content-addressed store for high-volume agent-provenance payloads is
a planned extension.
